SQL Identifiers
-------------------------------
Identifiers are the names used to identify database objects.
Database names, Table names, Column names, View names, Index names, Constraints, Triggers, Stored procedures.
While we are declaring an identifiers we have to fallow some rules and regulations.
Rules:
1.To only allowed characters to declare identifiers can contain a-z or A-Z or 0-9, _, $
2.Must be begin with a letter or _ symbol.
3.We can't declare identifiers with reserved keywords.
4.Spaces are not considered identifiers.
5.identifiers are case sensitive.
6.Max length to declare identifiers are 15 characters.

SQL(Structured Query Language):
-------------------------------
Structured Query language(SQL) is a standardized programming language specially designed for managing and manipulation relational databases. it provides declarative syntax that allows users to define what data they want retrieve, insert update or delete without specifying exactly how executes these operations.

Types of SQL commands:
----------------------
DDL(Data Definition Language)----> CREATE, ALTER, DROP, TRUNCATE, RENAME
DML(Data Manipulation Language)---->INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, LOCK
DCL(Data Control Language)---->GRANT, REVOKE
TCL(Transaction Control Language)---->COMMIT, ROLEBACK, SAVEPOINT
DQL(Data Query Language)---->SELECT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DDL(Data Definition Language)
-----------------------------
CREATE-->By using this command to create a new databases, tables, indexes, trigger, stored procedures etc.

Syntax: create database database-name
Example: create database DA3;
create table
